biography: The so-called Patron Saint of Princeton University, whose name is commemorated both in Nassau Hall and in the Princeton colors, William III, Prince of Orange & Nassau & King of England (1650-1702) was the Prince of Orange from birth, Stadtholder of the main provinces of the Dutch Republic from 1672 onwards, and King of England, Scotland, and Ireland from 1689. As King, he secured religious toleration and strengthened Parliament, granting independence to the judiciary in the Act of Settlement.
